7

Numerical Results

We perform the three stabilized finite element methods. We consider the L-shaped domain. We
study two exact solutions. The first is smooth of (H 1 (â„¦))2 , the second is singular and nearly
belongs to (H 2/3 (â„¦))2 . The L-shaped domain: â„¦ = (âˆ’1, 1) Ã— (âˆ’1, 1) \ (0, 1) Ã— (âˆ’1, 0), where
the reentrant corner is at (0, 0). We are given a smooth solution: u = (xex sin Ï€y, yey sin Ï€x).
Such solution is infinitely smooth, and of course, it belongs to (H 1 (â„¦))2 . In addition, we are
given a singular solution: u = (1 âˆ’ x2 )(1 âˆ’ y 2 )âˆ‡p, p = r2/3 sin 23 Î¸. This solution belongs to
(H 2/3âˆ’ (â„¦))2 , for any small constant  > 0. The regularity is less than one. In fact, the
solution takes an infinity at the reentrant corner. Theoretically, for smooth solution, Method
(A) and Method (C) give the optimal error bound O(h3 ), while Method (B) gives O(h) because
of the consistency error from the stabilization. For singular solution, the error bound for three
methods is the same as O(h2/3âˆ’ ). The singularity of the flux is usually due to the gradient
